<h2>Rise, set and visibility from different latitudes</h2>
<p> The asteroid rises and sets at different times depending on the observer's latitude and longitude. The plots below provide information for approximating when the asteroid will be visible, and how long it will be observable from a given location on a given date.</p>
<p>Plots are given for latitude intervals of 5&deg;, which is usually close enough for general planning purposes. Rise and set times are given in UTC for 0&deg; longitude. For other latitudes, these times will be approximate to the local time, which should again be sufficient for basic planning purposes. Note, however, that there will be an offset (typically &lt; 1/2 hr) for different longitudes, so if more accuracy is needed, then you should obtain a more detailed ephemeris.</p>

<h3>How to read these plots</h3>
<p>We provide a more detailed description of the Rise/Set and visibility plots, and an example of how to read the information <a href="Rise_Set/Rise_set_description.pdf" title="Explanation of how to read the	 Rise/Set and visibility (TimeUp) plots">here (PDF).</a></p>

